      4.0 out of 5 starsAmazon Vine Customer Review of Free Product
      Good watch for the price
      Reviewed in the United States on January 14, 2025
      I recently purchased the Hwagol Smart Watch, and it has been a pleasant surprise. Here are my thoughts: Pros: Versatile Features: This smartwatch comes packed with features like heart rate monitoring, sleep tracking, step counting, and even the ability... See more
      I recently purchased the Hwagol Smart Watch, and it has been a pleasant surprise. Here are my thoughts:

      Pros:

      Versatile Features: This smartwatch comes packed with features like heart rate monitoring, sleep tracking, step counting, and even the ability to make and receive calls. It's a great all-in-one device for fitness and daily use.
      Large Display: The 1.85-inch touchscreen is bright and responsive, making it easy to navigate through the various functions. The customizable watch faces add a nice personal touch.
      Battery Life: The battery life is impressive, lasting several days on a single charge. This is particularly useful for those who don't want to charge their watch every night.
      Affordable Price: Considering the range of features, the watch is reasonably priced. It offers great value for money compared to other smartwatches in the market.
      Stylish Design: The watch has a sleek and modern design that looks good on both men and women. It's comfortable to wear and fits well on the wrist.

      Cons:

      Band Quality: The quality of the band could be improved. It feels a bit flimsy and might not be as durable as the watch itself.
      Occasional Connection Issues: There are occasional issues with maintaining a stable connection to the phone, but these are relatively minor and infrequent.

      Overall: The Hwagol Smart Watch is a solid choice for anyone looking for a feature-rich and affordable smartwatch. Its versatile features, large display, and impressive battery life make it a great companion for both fitness tracking and everyday use.

    • Warm Sunshine
      5.0 out of 5 starsAmazon Vine Customer Review of Free Product
      It is a deal for the price.
      Reviewed in the United States on January 8, 2025
      This Hwagol smart watch uses CoFit app. The number of sports that can be tracked is limited to 4 and are Outdoor, Indoor, Cycling, and Climbing. However, when compared to MapMyRun App, the results are less than 3% different from each other. Having a smart watch on your... See more
      This Hwagol smart watch uses CoFit app. The number of sports that can be tracked is limited to 4 and are Outdoor, Indoor, Cycling, and Climbing. However, when compared to MapMyRun App, the results are less than 3% different from each other. Having a smart watch on your wrist can eliminate the need to carry the mobile phone on your body for certain activities and exercises that doesn't involve moving over a relatively large distance. The stats from tracking are distance, heart rate, time, calories, and number of steps. And my favorite feature of this watch is being able to control the music on my phone. However, if the phone is playing music through a connected Bluetooth speaker, there was problem with the music stopping after a number of songs or some amount of time instead of playing continuously. I haven't figured out what is the actual problem yet and will update when I do. With the heart rate monitoring set at every 30 minutes and the screen to stay on for 10 seconds, the battery lasted about 2 days, but the results are subjective and dependent on the amount of use. For the price, one can buy two smart watches if needed and have a backup when the battery needs to be charged. When not specifically tracking any workout, the watch automatically monitors the number of steps, the heart rate, calories burned, and the distance traveled. However, the distance traveled is not accurate because GPS feature is not actively turned on. And the number of calories used is also not accurate and seem to be about half of the result from MapMyRun app. The two strap flap holders slide too easily and thus don't hold the strap down properly. Overall, this rock bottom budget smart watch is much more useful than those non-smart old digital or mechanical watch. It is about time to move on from those old watches.

The stats from tracking are distance, heart rate, time, calories, and number of steps. And my favorite feature of this watch is being able to control the music on my phone. However, if the phone is playing music through a connected Bluetooth speaker, there was problem with the music stopping after a number of songs or some amount of time instead of playing continuously. I haven't figured out what is the actual problem yet and will update when I do. With the heart rate monitoring set at every 30 minutes and the screen to stay on for 10 seconds, the battery lasted about 2 days, but the results are subjective and dependent on the amount of use. For the price, one can buy two smart watches if needed and have a backup when the battery needs to be charged. When not specifically tracking any workout, the watch automatically monitors the number of steps, the heart rate, calories burned, and the distance traveled. However, the distance traveled is not accurate because GPS feature is not actively turned on. And the number of calories used is also not accurate and seem to be about half of the result from MapMyRun app. The two strap flap holders slide too easily and thus don't hold the strap down properly. Overall, this rock bottom budget smart watch is much more useful than those non-smart old digital or mechanical watch. It is about time to move on from those old watches.

      Decent fitness tracker, App required/privacy concern, multiple false claims, inaccurate monitors
      Reviewed in Canada on May 21, 2023
      1.
      This is a reasonably decent fitness tracker/smart watch that appears well-built and for the most part works as expected having all 3 common monitors (HR, BP, and SpO2) which is typical of these devices nowadays. However, 2 out of the 3 monitors (HR/BP) aren't exactly... See more
      This is a reasonably decent fitness tracker/smart watch that appears well-built and for the most part works as expected having all 3 common monitors (HR, BP, and SpO2) which is typical of these devices nowadays. However, 2 out of the 3 monitors (HR/BP) aren't exactly accurate or at least not adequately accurate to be useful for me and that's rather disappointing to see. Though, it does have a glucose monitor that most others don't have (and I have no idea whether it's accurate or not). It does have many of the standard features as most other budget or off-brand smart watches have and it has the typical silicone/rubber straps but it does have a metal buckle whereas many others have silicone/rubber/plastic one instead. In addition, it also comes with a stainless steel strap should you find the need for it. Unfortunately, it does NOT have metallic rose gold case/shell as depicted, and instead, the case/shell is completely made of a plastic which is rather disappointing to say the least. Furthermore, it does NOT have a GPS nor does it support a SIM card which is the primary reason for the order. Please stop using misleading ads that doesn't even match the specific product being sold. Note These so-called SMART WATCHES are really just FITNESS TRACKERS with added features (i.e. flashlight, calculator; mostly useless ones too) and it's NOT a true smart watch/device. A true smart device operates by itself on its own without the NEED to install an App for it to run and without depending on another device (i.e. your phone) to run. For instance, if your PHONE requires an App to be installed on a LAPTOP in order for various functions on your phone to work, or if your phone would lose certain features WHEN your laptop goes offline, would you consider your phone to be a SMART phone? Well, I wouldn't and I'll be extremely upset if that's the case, and that's exactly what happens here most of these so-called smart watches. ### Features By standard I don't mean one or two, in fact, the standard nowadays is about a dozen or so including heart rate, blood pressure, and oxygen monitor just to name a few. Unfortunately, although it does have all 3 monitors (HR/BP/SpO2) which is exactly what I want and need, the HR and BP don't seem to be accurate at all (SpO2 appears to be reasonably accurate for the most part although we know the figures for the vast majority of healthy people is usually either 98% or 99%) which is quite upsetting to have found out after numerous tests. It also has the typical sports and/or exercise related features that many others have. It has a reasonably large screen of 1.85" for a round case but this has been somewhat of a norm in 2023 so that's nothing to write home about either. I should also note that the advertised 100+ sports requires the app; otherwise, only a handful or so are available (which is more than most people would need under normal circumstance). Addition, it comes with 5 built-in watch faces which is quite typical albeit slightly less than what most others have nowadays. Battery It makes to claims to the battery capacity which is always a concern for me even though most of the advertised figures are nowhere near the true capacity. In either case, whatever the capacity might be, the only thing I really care is that it can last me an entire day (charge once a day is fine with me). With that being said, I also don't have a clue about the longevity of the battery but that's a common concern for all rechargeable smart watches out there (i.e. battery dies unexpected fast). Note that the default screen timeout is 5sec which is unusably short for me but it can be increased up to 15 seconds (whereas some other can't t at all while a few can do 60 sec) so that's good. I don't necessarily want 60 sec but it's nice to have the options (I set mine to 15sec). Water resistance Btw, these fitness trackers/smart watches are NOT meant to be submerged in water (salty or otherwise) longer than a few minute even though they advertised as being IP67 or even 5 ATM which is completely nonsensical if you know what that really means (around 30m under water but it's really meant for accidental submersion); otherwise, there is an extremely high probability that it will die prematurely. App For those who are curious about what the 'JYOUpro' app (2.8 rating) requires; Any data may be shared with other companies or organizations, including but not limited to; * Precise location * Email address and Phone number * Fitness info * SMS or MMS * Photos and videos * Files and docs * Contacts * Installed apps * Device or other IDs Data isn't encrypted (typical practice in China) Data is encrypted during transit Device & app history * read sensitive log data Contacts * read your contacts Location * approximate location (network-based) * precise location (GPS and network-based) Phone * directly call phone numbers * read call log * read phone status and identity * Photos/Media/Files * read the contents of your USB storage * modify or delete the contents of your USB storage Storage * read the contents of your USB storage * modify or delete the contents of your USB storage Camera * take pictures and videos Microphone * record audio Wi-Fi connection information * view Wi-Fi connections Device ID & call information * read phone status and identity Other * receive data from Internet * view network connections * pair with Bluetooth devices * access Bluetooth settings * control flashlight * full network access * run at startup * control vibration * prevent device from sleeping Note Like nearly all other budget smart watches (or any other 'smart' devices really) out there, an App is REQUIRED for this to function at its fullest which means you are giving the manufacturer (and whoever they decide to share it with or without your permission) AND the app OWNER (i.e. some company in China and that equates to the gov in this case) your COMPLETE and entire historical data. Some people consider some of these (i.e. precise GPS location, health info, heart rate, blood pressure, or the alike) to be 'extremely' personal information and therefore are private. Data mining, analysis, prediction, and eventually profit making and/or a form of control will be vital in many aspects of our lives in the foreseeable future. If this concerns you at all, look elsewhere. ### Value All things considered, this is a decent FITNESS TRACKER (with some smart watch functions) that works just fine if you don't care about any of the issues mentioned above, in particular the issues with the monitors (2 out of 3 monitors unfortunately). In addition, this appears to have plastic shell/case when it clearly advertised as being one that has a rose gold metallic shell which is completely misleading. Moreover, it also shows another watch with SIM/GPS capability as part of the ads for this watch that has neither feature which I do not appreciate. It's however reasonably priced at $40 for what it provides and its overall build quality and performance. Your mileage might vary.

      Battery
      It makes to claims to the battery capacity which is always a concern for me even though most of the advertised figures are nowhere near the true capacity. In either case, whatever the capacity might be, the only thing I really care is that it can last me an entire day (charge once a day is fine with me).

      With that being said, I also don't have a clue about the longevity of the battery but that's a common concern for all rechargeable smart watches out there (i.e. battery dies unexpected fast). Note that the default screen timeout is 5sec which is unusably short for me but it can be increased up to 15 seconds (whereas some other can't t at all while a few can do 60 sec) so that's good. I don't necessarily want 60 sec but it's nice to have the options (I set mine to 15sec).

      Water resistance
      Btw, these fitness trackers/smart watches are NOT meant to be submerged in water (salty or otherwise) longer than a few minute even though they advertised as being IP67 or even 5 ATM which is completely nonsensical if you know what that really means (around 30m under water but it's really meant for accidental submersion); otherwise, there is an extremely high probability that it will die prematurely.

      App
      For those who are curious about what the 'JYOUpro' app (2.8 rating) requires;

      Any data may be shared with other companies or organizations, including but not limited to;
      * Precise location
      * Email address and Phone number
      * Fitness info
      * SMS or MMS
      * Photos and videos
      * Files and docs
      * Contacts
      * Installed apps
      * Device or other IDs

      Data isn't encrypted (typical practice in China)
      Data is encrypted during transit

      Device & app history
      * read sensitive log data

      Contacts
      * read your contacts

      Location
      * approximate location (network-based)
      * precise location (GPS and network-based)

      Phone
      * directly call phone numbers
      * read call log
      * read phone status and identity
      * Photos/Media/Files
      * read the contents of your USB storage
      * modify or delete the contents of your USB storage

      Storage
      * read the contents of your USB storage
      * modify or delete the contents of your USB storage

      Camera
      * take pictures and videos

      Microphone
      * record audio

      Wi-Fi connection information
      * view Wi-Fi connections

      Device ID & call information
      * read phone status and identity

      Other
      * receive data from Internet
      * view network connections
      * pair with Bluetooth devices
      * access Bluetooth settings
      * control flashlight
      * full network access
      * run at startup
      * control vibration
      * prevent device from sleeping

      Note
      Like nearly all other budget smart watches (or any other 'smart' devices really) out there, an App is REQUIRED for this to function at its fullest which means you are giving the manufacturer (and whoever they decide to share it with or without your permission) AND the app OWNER (i.e. some company in China and that equates to the gov in this case) your COMPLETE and entire historical data.

      Some people consider some of these (i.e. precise GPS location, health info, heart rate, blood pressure, or the alike) to be 'extremely' personal information and therefore are private. Data mining, analysis, prediction, and eventually profit making and/or a form of control will be vital in many aspects of our lives in the foreseeable future. If this concerns you at all, look elsewhere.
      ###

      Value
      All things considered, this is a decent FITNESS TRACKER (with some smart watch functions) that works just fine if you don't care about any of the issues mentioned above, in particular the issues with the monitors (2 out of 3 monitors unfortunately). In addition, this appears to have plastic shell/case when it clearly advertised as being one that has a rose gold metallic shell which is completely misleading.

      Moreover, it also shows another watch with SIM/GPS capability as part of the ads for this watch that has neither feature which I do not appreciate. It's however reasonably priced at $40 for what it provides and its overall build quality and performance. Your mileage might vary.
